explanation:
For assessing whether any executed operations in OS_QueueCreate are dead code (i.e. removable without changing program behaviour) the analyzer needs the semantics and side-effects of the following symbols:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  - These input-validation macros can invoke error handling (e.g. log, return, abort). Knowing whether they can cause early exit or observable side-effects is required to decide if subsequent statements are ever relied upon.

- OS_CHECK_APINAME
  - As above: may validate the name and perform error-handling or logging (possibly via OS_printf). Must know if it alters control-flow or global state.

- OS_CHECK_SIZE
  - Size validation macro; could abort/return or mutate state. Its behaviour affects whether later assignments are redundant.

- ARGCHECK
  - Used for the queue_depth <= OS_QUEUE_MAX_DEPTH check. The macro could trigger error handling (and thus make later code unreachable or necessary), so its semantics matter.

- OS_QUEUE_MAX_DEPTH
  - The constant used in the ARGCHECK condition. Necessary to know the effective condition and whether the check ever fires.

- OS_QUEUE_INVALID_SIZE
  - Error code passed to ARGCHECK. Needed to understand error paths and observable behaviour of the check.

- OS_printf
  - Present in the static-call graph as a potential side-effect of checks. If validation macros call OS_printf (or similar reporting), that is an observable behavior preventing removal of code that produces messages.

- OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew
  - Central to control-flow: allocates an object id/token and (per comment) locks the object type. It has important side-effects (allocation, locking, possible failure return codes). Whether removing subsequent operations changes the system depends on its behaviour.

- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE
  - The object-type argument to OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew influences which global tables/locks are affected; needed to reason about side-effects and whether the allocation is meaningful.

- OS_object_token_t
  - Token type semantics (e.g. whether it can be NULL, contains indices) affect whether subsequent table access is valid or redundant.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET
  - Macro/function that maps the token to the internal table entry (queue pointer). If it can produce side-effects (index validation, error logging) or if it can return a pointer used elsewhere, this affects whether writes to that table are necessary.

- OS_queue_table
  - The actual global table referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET. Whether entries are shared globally makes the assignments to queue->max_depth/max_size observable.

- OS_OBJECT_INIT
  - Macro that initializes the object table entry and stores the name; this may publish the object to other subsystems, set state flags, or trigger further side-effects — critical to determine if the initialization is required.

- OS_queue_internal_record_t
  - Structure layout and semantics (which fields are volatile/used elsewhere) determine whether writing max_depth/max_size is observable or can be removed.

- OS_QueueCreate_Impl
  - The OS-specific create routine is called after populating the record. It likely reads the table entry and performs platform actions (resource allocation, kernel queue creation). Its side-effects make prior writes meaningful; conversely, if it always fails or doesn't use the table, some writes could be dead — so its behaviour must be known.

- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew
  - Finalizes the allocation and (per comment) unlocks global table, possibly notifies events and returns the final object id. It has side-effects (unlock, notification) that are required to preserve system behaviour; removing it would change locking/notification semantics.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The value compared against return_code controls whether the if-block executes. Knowing its value and the return semantics of callees matters to see if the block is ever executed (and thus whether its inner statements are dead).

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken
  - Appears in the call-graph as related to token-to-index operations; macros like OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET / OS_OBJECT_INIT may use it. Its semantics (e.g. validation, side-effects) can make table accesses observable.

- OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken
  - May be used by the init/get macros to compute global ids or bases; needed to reason about side-effects and published identifiers.

- OS_NotifyEvent
  - Called by the object-id allocation/finalize routines (per call graph). Notifications are observable side-effects — if present, they prevent removal of the calling code as dead.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit
  - Internal function invoked by allocation: starts the transaction/lock. Required to understand lock side-effects that would be left if Finalize is removed.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish
  - Internal function invoked by Finalize: ends transaction/lock and may perform publish/cleanup. Knowing this is necessary to judge whether omitting Finalize (or the allocate) would change behaviour.

Rationale summary: to determine whether any operations inside OS_QueueCreate (initialization of table entry, assignments to queue fields, call to OS_QueueCreate_Impl, and Finalize) are dead, the analyzer must know which macros/functions produce observable side-effects (logging, notifications, global state publication, locking/unlocking, OS-specific resource creation) and which only update local/non-observable state. The symbols above either are called directly by OS_QueueCreate or are used by the macros it invokes and therefore are required to correctly judge dead vs. necessary code.
